column11: At 92 years of age, Robert Mugabe has ruled Zimbabwe since 1987 and has resisted naming a successor (Reuters). Despite the fact that the constitution provides for an orderly succession with the first Vice President taking office in the event of the president's death, the question of succession continues to dominate politics in Zimbabwe (Deutsche Welle, Newsweek, International Business Times). Recommended Questions When will Pierre Nkurunziza cease to be president of Burundi? Will Jacob Zuma cease to be president of South Africa before 1 January 2017? Emmerson Mnangagwa is the new president of Zimbabwe (NY Times). This question closed as ‚Äúa) Emmerson Mnangagwa,‚Äù with an end date of 24 November 2017. Zimbabwe's Mnangagwa to be sworn in as president on Friday (Reuters) Zimbabwe's former vice president Emmerson Mnangagwa will be sworn in as president on Friday following the resignation of Robert Mugabe after nearly four decades in power, state broadcaster ZBC reported today. With Mugabe‚Äôs resignation, the situation in Zimbabwe remains confounding. ZANU - PF, the current military apparatus, essentially ZANU - PF dominant, and the alignment with Mnangagwa, essentially keeps the instruments of an autocratic state in place. Mnangagwa, a close ally of Mugabe and the ‚Äòliberation movement structures‚Äô in Southern Africa (and the SADC aligned states), maintain domestic and regional power. Mnangagwa, responsible with Mugabe and ZANU -PF for the slaughter of 100,000s of Ndebele opposition, resistance and civilians, is no different from Mugabe‚Äôs autocratic coercion and dictatorial governance. While the current population are elated at recent events, it is necessary to ask whether there is mass illusion, acquiesce, or irrationality at a national and a domestic level. Even though Mnangagwa is currently head of ZANU - PF, will he simply be installed as state president by party rule? Will the ruling party simply bypass the constitutional requirements of electoral processes? Will the military (a coup claimed as a non coup) rule, in the interim to appease international and domestic actors and investors who require stability? The ideological nature of the Zimbabwean population, the state, party ( essentially identical in nature) continues to rest on the Leninist/Stalinist authoritarian paradigm, supported by a majority of SADC states (dressed in democratic policies, but essentially derive from the same ideological roots in the alliances, with the exception of Botswana and perhaps 1 other) will not change its political nature by a ‚Äònon coup event‚Äô. The dynamics of authoritarian - relative democratic transition is complex in nature, and requires rebalancing an entire social structure through dynamic ‚Äòrevolution‚Äô. What does does this portend for violent/ peaceful change? Military structures do not refrain from rule after its taste of power. The empirics of its politics and how it comport with reality belies a reliance on the current mass delusion of democratic change. This leaves the question of whether Zimbabwe will have a president and maintenance of its political structure before 2018? I suspect that it will not occur prior to 2018 without the tightening of international constraints by economic and political actors who seek to democratize the region and Zimbabwe in particular. The vacuum of military rule until president is lawfully I stalled will take some time.

I think this question has become a guessing game, for at least three reasons: 1. Zimbabwe media relies more on opinion than information and the international press is no better informed. Some of this is due to partisanship, but it's also clear that there is a dearth of reliable information to draw from. What isn't clear is whether this is a result of deliberate obfuscation from those near to Mugabe, or whether it's because no-one actually has a clue what's going on. 2. There's plenty of scuttlebutt suggesting Grace is next in line, but this would surely be a disastrous decision. Would it be seen as a dynastic succession? If so, it's more likely to galvanize opponents than unite the party and the nation. The problem, however, is that no-one from the inner circle may be able to bring all the factions together. The threat of a coup will be real for some time. 3. Mugabe may be quite mad. At the very least, he is blind to the needs of his people. As he currently spends more time abroad than at home it is hard to know if he is much more than president in-name-only. With this in mind, I don't think it's too silly to wonder if the line about Mugabe being "president for life" is more than just talk. If old Bob completely loses his marbles or falls into a coma, will he still officially be president? How might GJO score this question if a) someone is appointed acting president or b) the new president is overthrown within a few weeks?
